english:
  title: A Letter in My Own Hand to the Venerable Monk Myogyeom
  author: Lee Gyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    On this day of this month, I humbly write to you.

    I have long borne the reputation of a madman in this world. Only Minister Yun does not treat me as such a madman, and in the Buddhist gates, only you, Venerable One, show me the same regard. Each time we meet, you receive me with joy and show no haste to part. I too am not unaware of this kindness. Yet worldly ties bind me heavily, and day after day I cannot come as often as I wish to be in your presence. How can I not blush with shame?

    But among the complaints I harbor in our spiritual friendship, there is one small grievance I cannot suppress. You have taken my poems and writings, entrusted them to a merchant ship returning to Song, and sent them forth to spread through the Middle Kingdom. This is not a kindness to me—it merely exposes my ugliness. I am scarcely more than a clerk who understands Chinese characters, like a mere servant of the Middle Kingdom. When the Chinese see my poetry, they will surely say: "Is this all? The poets of the Three Koreas are not limited to this one man. That only his poetry has traveled to China suggests he must be a great master of his nation. Yet even the great produce no more than this. What then of the rest?" Should they speak thus, we only reveal the shortcomings of our country. I beg you, send nothing more.

    What troubles me most is that you, Venerable One, are not yet advanced in years, yet you have fallen grievously ill, and your face grows thinner with each passing day. Though one who has attained the Way regards life and death with indifference, I remain bound to the sentiments of this world and cannot help but fear for you. I can only pray that you cherish yourself for the sake of the Dharma, apply yourself diligently to medicine and nourishment, and thus answer the earnest prayers for your longevity that we and all the Buddhist community offer up.

    The rest I shall explain when we meet. There is more to say, but I must leave it unsaid. I bow twice.
  footnotes:
    - The Three Koreas (三韓) refers to the ancient Korean kingdoms and, by extension, Korea itself.
    - Lee Gyubo expresses concern that sending his work to China will invite unfavorable comparisons and damage Korea's reputation, as his poetry may not meet Chinese standards.
    - The letter is written in the formal epistolary style of Classical Chinese, using humble self-references and respectful forms of address appropriate to correspondence with a Buddhist monk.
